11. Proof: Let $g(x)=\frac{f(x)+f(-x)}{2}, h(x)=\frac{f(x)-f(-x)}{2}$, then $f(x)=g(x)+h(x)$, and $g(x)$ is an even function, $h(x)$ is an odd function, for any $x \in \mathbf{R}, g(x+2 \pi)=g(x), h(x+2 \pi)=h(x)$.
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\text { Let } f_{1}(x)=\frac{g(x)+g(x+\pi)}{2}, f_{2}(x)=\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
\frac{g(x)-g(x+\pi)}{2 \cos x} & x \neq k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2} \\
0 & x=k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}
\end{array},\right. \\
f_{3}(x)=\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
\frac{h(x)-h(x+\pi)}{2 \sin x} & x \neq k \pi \\
0 & x=k \pi
\end{array}\right. \\
f_{4}(x)=\left\{\begin{array}{ll}
\frac{h(x)+h(x+\pi)}{2 \sin 2 x} & x \neq \frac{k \pi}{2} \\
0 & x=\frac{k \pi}{2}
\end{array}, \text { where } k\right. \text { is any integer. }
\end{array}
$$

It is easy to verify that $f_{i}(x), i=1,2,3,4$ are even functions, and for any $x \in \mathbf{R}, f_{i}(x+\pi)=f_{i}(x), i=1,2,3,4$. We now prove that for any $x \in \mathbf{R}$, $f_{1}(x)+f_{2}(x) \cos x=g(x)$. When $x \neq k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}$, it is clearly true; when $x=k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}$, since $f_{1}(x)+f_{2}(x) \cos x=f_{1}(x)=\frac{g(x)+g(x+\pi)}{2}$,

and $g(x+\pi)=g\left(k \pi+\frac{3 \pi}{2}\right)=g\left(k \pi+\frac{3 \pi}{2}-2(k+1) \pi\right)=g\left(-k \pi-\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=g\left(k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=g(x)$, hence for any $x \in \mathbf{R}, f_{1}(x)+f_{2}(x) \cos x=g(x)$.

We now prove that for any $x \in \mathbf{R}$, $f_{3}(x) \sin x+f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x=h(x)$. When $x \neq \frac{k \pi}{2}$, it is clearly true; when $x=k \pi$, $h(x)=h(k \pi)=h(k \pi-2 k \pi)=h(-k \pi)=-h(k \pi)$, so $h(x)=h(k \pi)=0$, and at this time $f_{3}(x) \sin x+$ $f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x=0$,

hence $h(x)=f_{3}(x) \sin x+f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x$; when $x=k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}$, $h(x+\pi)=h\left(k \pi+\frac{3 \pi}{2}\right)=h\left(k \pi+\frac{3 \pi}{2}-\right.$ $2(k+1) \pi)=h\left(-k \pi-\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=-h\left(k \pi+\frac{\pi}{2}\right)=-h(x)$,

hence $f_{3}(x) \sin x=\frac{h(x)-h(x+\pi)}{2}=h(x)$, and $f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x=0$, thus $h(x)=f_{3}(x) \sin x+$ $f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x$.
Therefore, for any $x \in \mathbf{R}$, $f_{3}(x) \sin x+f_{4}(x) \sin 2 x=h(x)$. In summary, the conclusion is proved.

